<!-- SC_OFF --><div class="md"><p>So I use tags for my org tasks like: <code>@anywhere</code>, <code>@computer</code>, <code>@work</code>, and <code>@home</code>. There&#39;s a hierarchical structure here, sort of like this:</p> <pre><code>@anywhere @computer @work @home </code></pre> <p>So from my agenda, I&#39;d like to be able to filter for e.g. <code>@work</code> when I&#39;m on my work computer, and have all tasks labeled as <code>@anywhere</code>, <code>@computer</code>, or <code>@work</code> show up. The problem is, org&#39;s <a href="https://orgmode.org/manual/Tag-Hierarchy.html">Tag Hierarchy</a> seems to work in the opposite way that I want; when I create a hierarchy like this:</p> <pre><code>(setq org-tag-alist &#39;((:startgrouptag) (&quot;@anywhere&quot;) (:grouptags) (:startgrouptag) (&quot;@computer&quot;) (:grouptags) (&quot;@work&quot;) (&quot;@home&quot;) (:endgrouptag) (:endgrouptag)) </code></pre> <p>Then filter by e.g. <code>@work</code>, I only get <code>@work</code>-tagged entries. On the other hand, when I reverse the hierarchy like this:</p> <pre><code>(setq org-tag-alist &#39;((:startgrouptag) (&quot;@work&quot;) (:grouptags) (&quot;@anywhere&quot;) (&quot;@computer&quot;) (:endgrouptag) (:startgrouptag) (&quot;@home&quot;) (:grouptags) (&quot;@anywhere&quot;) (&quot;@computer&quot;) (:endgrouptag)) </code></pre> <p>I can filter by <code>@work</code> or <code>@home</code> and get the results I want, however I <em>can&#39;t</em> filter by <code>@computer</code> and see all <code>@work</code>/<code>@home</code>/<code>@computer</code>/<code>@anywhere</code>-tagged entries. And, unfortunately, if I add a grouptag section for <code>@computer</code>, it includes children of that group in <code>@work</code> and <code>@home</code> now, corrupting those groups.</p> <p>So my question is: is there a better way to filter to include a child in a hierarchy OR its parents? FWIW I&#39;ve also tried using the <code>|</code> operator in my filter query (e.g. <code>@work|@anywhere</code>) but org doesn&#39;t seem to parse it, and it does no filtering (it gives me a message like <code>@work|@anywhere filter ignored because tag/category is not represented</code>).</p> <p>&#x200B;</p> <p>(btw, I&#39;m using doom emacs, in case that happens to be relevant here)</p> </div><!-- SC_ON --> &#32; submitted by &#32; <a href="https://www.reddit.com/user/C-x_M-c_M-butterfly"> /u/C-x_M-c_M-butterfly </a> <br/> <span><a href="https://www.reddit.com/r/emacs/comments/1394mvt/what_is_the_right_way_to_use_orgagendafilter_with/">[link]</a></span> &#32; <span><a href="https://www.reddit.com/r/emacs/comments/1394mvt/what_is_the_right_way_to_use_orgagendafilter_with/">[comments]</a></span>